const bookIntroductions = {
    // OLD TESTAMENT
    "Genesis": "Genesis is the first book in the Bible. The word ‘Genesis’ means ‘beginning’. \n\nGenesis is a book about events that happened a long time ago. It tells us about the first humans, Adam and Eve, and their descendants, Cain, Abel and Noah. \n\nIt also tells us about Abraham and Sarah. Abraham was the first ancestor of the nation of Israel, and other nations. He was the father of Isaac and Ishmael, and the grandfather of Jacob. \n\nIt tells us about Jacob, and how God changed his name to Israel. Jacob's sons became the ancestors of the 12 tribes of Israel. \n\nIt tells us about Joseph who was one of Jacob's sons. The Book of Genesis also teaches us many important things that we need to know. \n\nIt teaches us about the world, about ourselves, and about God. It explains that God made the world. \n\nIt tells us that God filled the world with beautiful plants and animals. It tells us that he made men and women. Everything that God made was very good. It explains how the first man and woman refused to obey God. And it explains that everyone has had trouble and pain in their lives since that time. It also tells us about God's promise to bless the people of all the world's nations.",
    "Exodus": "In the Book of Genesis, we read about Jacob and his son Joseph. Joseph's brothers sold him as a slave, to work in Egypt. Later, there was a famine and all of Jacob's family went to live in Egypt.\n\nExodus continues the story. Jacob had many descendants. The king of Egypt made them his slaves. But God chose Moses to lead them out of Egypt.\n\nExodus tells us how God led them through the desert. It tells us how God gave his Law to Moses for the Israelites. It also tells us how the Israelites built the tabernacle and how they worshipped God there.\n\nThe word ‘Exodus’ means a large number of people who are leaving a place.",
    "Leviticus": "In this book, Moses tells the Israelites the rules that God wants them to obey. God showed his people that he is holy, and they must worship him in the right way.\n\nIn Chapters 1–7, God tells Moses the rules for sacrifices that the Israelites must offer. The Book of Hebrews tells us that these sacrifices pointed to Jesus. His death was a perfect sacrifice. It means that the Old Testament sacrifices are no longer necessary.\n\nIn Chapters 8–10, God tells Moses the rules for priests. Aaron was Moses' brother. He was the first priest that God gave to the Israelites. The Book of Hebrews tells us that Jesus is the perfect priest.\n\nChapters 11–27 tell us that the Israelites must live in the right way. They must do clean things. They must love their neighbours. If they obey God, they will be happy. If they do not, much trouble will happen to them.\n\nChapter 16 tells us about a very special day called the Day of Atonement. On that day, the people used two goats. One of the goats was a sin offering. The priest sent the other goat into the desert. It was a sign to the people that their sin could go away like the goat.",
    "Numbers": "This book tells us about the Israelites as they travelled from Egypt to a land called Canaan. It was a difficult journey through a desert.\n\nMoses was the man that the Lord chose to lead the Israelites out of Egypt. Aaron was Moses' brother. He was the first priest for the Israelites.\n\nMany times, the Israelites did not obey God. They complained about the journey. They did not trust God to take care of them. Then God had to punish them. So the journey took 40 years. All the men who started the journey died on the way.\n\nChapters 1-10 describe what happened at a mountain called Sinai. They tell us about the Israelites at the start of their journey.\n\nChapters 11-20 describe what happened in the desert, near to a place called Kadesh.\n\nChapters 21-36 describe what happened when the Israelites arrived near to Canaan.",
    "Deuteronomy": "God chose Moses to lead the Israelites out of Egypt. Moses knew God and he loved God's Law. God talked to him like a friend.\n\nIn this book, Moses explains to the Israelites what God has done to help them. God brought them out of Egypt. He was their guide through the desert for 40 years. God gave his Law to them at Mount Sinai.\n\nThe Israelites have now arrived near the Jordan River. They will go across the river into Canaan, the land that God promised to give to them. But Moses will not go with them. God has told him that he will die before the Israelites go across the river. So Moses wants them to remember that they belong to God as his people, and that God loves them. He tells them again about all the commands and rules that God wants them to obey. If they obey him, they will be happy. But if they do not obey God, much trouble will happen to them.",
    "Joshua": "The Israelites had travelled for 40 years in the desert while Moses was their leader. All the men that God had brought out of Egypt had died. Moses had died, too. Now God had chosen Joshua to be their leader. He was one of the 12 men who had gone to look at Canaan, the land that God had promised to give to the Israelites. He and Caleb had not been afraid of the people who lived there. He trusted God to help them. The other 10 men had been too afraid. See Numbers 14.\n\nGod would not let Moses himself go across the Jordan River into Canaan. Joshua was the person that God wanted to lead the Israelites into the land that would be their new home.\n\nThe name ‘Joshua’ means ‘God saves’. The name ‘Jesus’ also means the same.\n\nThe Book of Joshua tells how God helped his people to make their home in Canaan. It tells us how God stopped the water in the Jordan River. Then the Israelites could go across into Canaan. It tells us how the Israelites won many battles when they obeyed God.\n\nIt shows that God did what he had promised to do for his people.",
    "Judges": "This book tells us about the Israelites after they entered the land of Canaan. It talks about the judges, who were people that God chose to lead them and keep them safe from their enemies.\n\nIt tells us how the people did not obey God. They worshipped idols instead of God. When they did this, God punished them and they were sorry. When they were sorry, they asked God to help them. So God sent another judge to save them. Then they stopped obeying God again. This happened many times.\n\nThe Book of Judges teaches us how important it is to obey God. But if people who have stopped obeying God are sorry and turn to him, he is always ready to save them.",
    "Ruth": "This book is about a woman called Ruth. She was from a country called Moab. She was not an Israelite but she married an Israelite man. Ruth was a good woman. She was very kind to her husband's mother, Naomi. They were very poor and Naomi was very sad. But Ruth and Naomi obeyed God.\n\nA man called Boaz helped them and he married Ruth. God blessed Ruth and Boaz. They had children and Naomi became happy again. King David and Jesus were both descendants of Ruth. See Matthew 1:5-6; Luke 3:32.",
    "I Samuel": "The books of 1 Samuel and 2 Samuel were once one book. God's prophet Samuel is the first important person that we read about in this book. He died about 930 BC.\n\nBefore kings ruled Israel, their leaders were called ‘judges’. They were leaders of the Israelites for about 350 years after Joshua died. Samuel was the last of Israel's judges. He was also a prophet. Samuel anointed Saul to be the first king of Israel. But Saul did not obey God. So God chose another king, David, who would obey him. 1 Samuel finishes with the death of King Saul.\n\nDavid won many fights against Israel's enemies. He killed a very big man called Goliath. People said that David was a better fighter than King Saul. So Saul tried many times to kill David. But God kept David safe.",
    "II Samuel": "The books of 1 and 2 Samuel were once one book.\n\nAt the end of 1 Samuel, we read about the deaths of King Saul and his son, Jonathan.\n\n2 Samuel tells us about David as Israel's king. He won many fights against Israel's enemies. He obeyed God for almost all his life, and God was happy with him.\n\nBut sometimes David did not obey God. When David said sorry to God, God forgave him. But because David did some wrong things, his own family sometimes gave him trouble.",
    "I Kings": "1 Kings is a book about the Israelites. The Books of 1 Kings and 2 Kings tell us what happened after King David ruled Israel. Solomon became king after David. He built the first temple in Jerusalem.\n\nAfter Solomon died, Israel became two kingdoms. The kingdom in the south was called Judah. Its capital city was Jerusalem. Rehoboam was the first king of Judah. The kingdom in the north was still called Israel. Its capital city was Samaria. Jeroboam became king of Israel. See 1 Kings 12. There were many other kings who ruled after these two kings.\n\nWhen the kings of Judah and Israel obeyed God, the people had peace. But sometimes the kings and the people did not obey God. They worshipped other gods instead. Then bad things happened. God sent a prophet to warn the people. His name was Elijah. He did miracles that someone could only do with God's help. He told the people that they must worship God.",
    "II Kings": "2 Kings is a book about the Israelites. The Books of 1 Kings and 2 Kings tell us what happened after King David ruled Israel. Solomon became king after David.\n\nAfter Solomon died, the nation of Israel became two kingdoms. The kingdom in the south was called Judah. Its capital city was Jerusalem. The kingdom in the north was still called Israel. It was also called Samaria because that was the name of its capital city.\n\n2 Kings continues the history of the two kingdoms, Judah and Israel, and their rulers. The most important prophet in 2 Kings is Elisha, who took Elijah's place. He told the people that they should worship only God.\n\nAfter Elisha died, many of the kings were very bad. In the end, God decided to send his people away from their land. This happened to the northern kingdom of Israel first. Then it happened to the people of Judah, who belonged to the tribes of Judah and Benjamin. God did not let his people go back to their land for about 70 years.",
    "I Chronicles": "1 Chronicles is a book about the history of the Israelites. Some of the book tells us about the same time that we read about in 2 Samuel.\n\nThe book begins with a list of the families of the Israelites. Then it tells us about the time when David ruled over all Israel. It also tells us a lot about how the people worshipped God. The last part of the book describes David's plans to build a temple for God in Jerusalem. David gave careful rules to the priests. He wanted everyone in the temple to serve God properly.\n\nThe book tells us how David put the workers in the temple into groups. He made lists of the priests and the Levites who would be leaders of the worship in the temple. God did not let David build the temple. But David prepared the materials so that his son, Solomon, would be able to build it. In the next book, 2 Chronicles, we can read how Solomon built the temple.",
    "II Chronicles": "This book tells us about the Israelites from the time of King Solomon. It tells us more about some of the things that we can read in 1 Kings and 2 Kings.\n\nThe first 9 chapters are about Solomon. He built the first temple in Jerusalem.\n\nWhen Solomon died, the nation of Israel divided into two kingdoms. The kingdom in the north was still called Israel. The kingdom in the south was called Judah.\n\nThe other chapters of 2 Chronicles are about the kings of Judah. Some of them were good kings but many of them were bad. They did not worship God. God sent prophets to tell them to turn back to him, but they still did not worship him. So God sent the Babylonians to take the people of Israel away from their land for about 70 years.",
    "Ezra": "Ezra and Nehemiah are the last two books about the history of the Israelites.\n\nNebuchadnezzar, the king of Babylon, had destroyed the temple in Jerusalem. He took the Israelites who lived in Judah to Babylon as prisoners. That was called the Exile.\n\nWhen Cyrus, King of Persia, started to rule over Babylon, he told the Jews to return to Jerusalem. He told them to build God's temple again. The Book of Ezra tells us how the Jews did that. This happened in about 538 BC.\n\nThen Ezra returned to Jerusalem. Ezra was a priest who studied God's Law. He taught the people how they should live to please God in their own land.",
    "Nehemiah": "The Book of Nehemiah continues the story that starts in the Book of Ezra.\n\nNebuchadnezzar, the king of Babylon, had destroyed the temple in Jerusalem. He took the Israelites who lived in Judah to Babylon as prisoners. That was called the Exile.\n\nWhen Cyrus, king of Persia, started to rule over Babylon, he let some of the Jews return to Jerusalem. They built the temple again. We can read about that in the Book of Ezra.\n\nLater, Artaxerxes became king of Babylon. He let more Jews return from Babylon to Jerusalem with Nehemiah. This book tells us about what happened.\n\nNehemiah found that soldiers had destroyed the city wall. He helped the Jews to build the wall again. Their enemies tried to stop them. Nehemiah helped the people to be brave and to continue the work. He knew that God would keep them safe.",
    "Esther": "The Book of Esther tells us about a Jewish woman called Esther.\n\nThe king of Babylon had taken the Israelites away from Judah as prisoners. He took them to Babylon. That happened in about the year 586 BC. The book tells us what happened when King Xerxes ruled Persia, a country near Babylon. He ruled from about 486 to 465 BC.\n\nThe Book of Esther does not use the word ‘God’ at all. But it shows us how God was working at that time. He kept his people, the Jews, safe when they were in danger.\n\nIt shows us that God listens to our prayers. It shows us that he has the power to make things happen as he wants them to. It shows us that he loves his own people and he keeps them safe. And it shows us that he has a purpose for his people.",
    "Job": "In this book we read the story of a man called Job. Job was a rich man with a big family. But Satan destroyed everything that belonged to him. Satan killed all of Job's children and made Job very ill.\n\nJob was a very good man. He did not understand why such bad things happened to him. He had three friends who tried to give him answers to his problems. But their words did not help Job to feel happier. Then another man tried to help. But Job did not think that he really understood the problem either.\n\nAt the end of the story, God speaks to Job. Then Job understands that he cannot know everything. Only God knows everything. Only God is completely powerful. But we, like Job, must trust God, even if bad things happen in our lives.",
    "Psalms": "The Book of Psalms contains 150 songs called psalms. They were written hundreds of years before Jesus lived on earth.\n\nMost of the psalms show the name of the writer at the top. King David wrote many of them.\n\nThe writers wrote the psalms for several different purposes. In some psalms, they remembered what God had done for his people in the past. There are happy psalms that praise God because he is great and good. In other psalms, the writers pray to God for help. They ask him to save them. Sometimes they pray that God will forgive them for the bad things that they have done. In some psalms, the writers ask God to destroy their enemies.\n\nMany of the psalms look to future times when God's special king, the Messiah, will rule everything.\n\nThe psalms show how God worked in the lives of his people. They include many things that still happen in the lives of people today. Many people find help as they read the Psalms. We can read them when we are happy and we want to praise God. We can also read them when we are sad and we need God to help us. If we trust God, we know that he will help us in our trouble.\n\nThe psalms tell us how great and powerful God is. They show us that bad things make him angry. They also show how much he loves us.",
    "Proverbs": "Many people know proverbs in their own language. Often the proverbs are very old. Nobody knows who first said them. They are usually short and powerful, so that people can remember them.\n\nKing Solomon wrote down the proverbs in this book. They are proverbs that he heard people say at different times. These proverbs tell us how to live in a good way. They tell us what it means to be really wise. Solomon was a wise person himself. To be wise is not the same as to be clever. To be wise means to know the way that God wants us to live.\n\nMany proverbs show the difference between a wise person and a foolish person. In the Book of Proverbs, a ‘fool’ means someone who refuses to let God teach him what is good and right. Other proverbs show the difference between a good person who is honest and righteous, and a wicked person who deceives people and who tells lies.\n\nProverbs are not laws or rules. Each proverb shows us a picture of something that is true about life, but it does not tell us everything. Proverbs make us think carefully about how we live our lives.",
    "Ecclesiastes": "We do not know who wrote the Book of Ecclesiastes. He was a king and some people think that he was King Solomon. He calls himself ‘the Teacher’. He was a wise man but he realized that wisdom did not give all the answers about life. Many people try to find reasons for all the things that happen in life. But they cannot always find reasons that they can understand. He tells us what this is like. It is like somebody who tries to catch the wind. He means that it is not possible to find all the answers to life.\n\nWhen the Teacher uses the words ‘on the earth’, it means that he is leaving God out of his thoughts. Things that happen ‘on the earth’ seem to have no purpose if we do not believe that God rules from above.\n\nThe Teacher uses the words ‘wise’ and ‘wisdom’ many times. If people want to be really wise, they need to know how God sees things. We will still have questions about our life on the earth. Some of them are questions that nobody can answer. At the end of the book, the Teacher says that we need to know what God wants. We need to listen to him and obey him. He gave us life. When our life ends, we will have to explain to him how we have lived.",
    "Song of Solomon": "Solomon was a very rich king of Israel. He lived more than 900 years before Jesus Christ. He wrote down many songs and proverbs. ‘Song of Songs’ means that this is the best song of all the songs that he wrote down.\n\nThis book has poems about love. It is about love between a man and a woman. In some of the poems, the man is speaking to the woman. In other poems, the woman is speaking to the man. There are also other people, like the woman's friends. We are not always sure who is speaking which poem, but we have shown which person is probably speaking in each place.\n\nBecause these are poems, there is a lot of picture language. A word or a group of words can mean two things. Words like ‘vineyard’ or ‘garden’ may describe something beautiful, like the woman's body. We see this in Chapter 4, when the man and woman enjoy each other's bodies.\n\nSome people think that the poems are a picture of the love between God and his people.",
    "Isaiah": "Isaiah was a prophet. A prophet tells people what God is saying. Isaiah spoke God's messages from about 740 BC to about 687 BC. He gave God's messages to the people of Judah. Judah was the name of the Israelite kingdom in the south.\n\nIsaiah spoke about what was happening during his life. In about 701 BC, the king of Assyria attacked Judah with his army but God rescued Judah's people (Isaiah 36-37).\n\nIsaiah also spoke about what would happen in the future. He spoke about what would happen to Judah and to Israel. Israel was the name of the kingdom in the north. Isaiah also says ‘Ephraim’ and ‘Samaria’ as names for the northern kingdom. He also spoke about what would happen to some other countries near to Israel.\n\nIsaiah spoke about a future King who would be a descendant of King David. This King would come to save his people. He would also bring light to the nations of the world. Isaiah spoke about a child called Immanuel who would have no human father (Isaiah 7:14). This child would rule fairly, with great authority (Isaiah 9:6-7). He would be God's servant (Isaiah 42:1-9). God's servant would die so that God could forgive his people (Isaiah 53:1-11). Then, God would put his servant in a place of great honour (Isaiah 53:11-12). God calls everyone to come and receive his free gift (Isaiah 55).\n\nIn the New Testament, we see that Jesus is the King that God promised to send. Jesus says that Isaiah's message is speaking about him (Luke 4:16-21).\n\nIsaiah also spoke about new heavens and a new earth that God will make (Isaiah 65:17-25). This is still in the future.",
    "Jeremiah": "Jeremiah was a priest. He was born in Anathoth, a town in Israel, in about 650 BC. The Lord told Jeremiah that he must be his prophet. He told Jeremiah what messages he must speak to the people of Judah.\n\nJeremiah was afraid, but the Lord promised to make him strong. So he went and told the people what the Lord had told him to say. He did this for 40 years, but it was very difficult. The Lord told the people that they were very bad. So the people became angry. Jeremiah was very brave and he continued to speak the Lord's words. He wanted people to stop doing bad things. God would not punish them if they turned back to him. Jeremiah knew that. But the people did not listen, so God had to punish them. This made Jeremiah very sad.\n\nBut God showed Jeremiah that he would never leave his people alone. God himself would, one day, bring many people to know him. He would make a new covenant with his people. They would know how to please God, without rules that were written down (Jeremiah 31:31-34). There would be a descendant of King David who would rule for ever (Jeremiah 33:14-16).\n\nIn the New Testament, we see that Jesus is the King that God promised to send. Jesus gives the Holy Spirit to his people so that they know how to please God.",
    "Lamentations": "Lamentations is a book about sad things. The book has five chapters. The first four chapters are alphabet poems. Each verse, or group of verses, starts with the next letter of the Hebrew alphabet.\n\nGod wanted his people to take care of Jerusalem and his temple. He wanted his people to worship him in the temple. But the people who lived in Jerusalem did not obey God. Finally, he became angry with them. He brought armies from another country to destroy Jerusalem and to take the people away.\n\nWe think that the prophet Jeremiah wrote Lamentations.\n\nLamentations shows us that God gets angry about sin. He is happy when we change the way that we live and we turn back to him. This book also shows us what God wants. He wants us to love him. He wants us to obey him. If we do that, he will help us to be good and to do good things.",
    "Ezekiel": "Ezekiel belonged to the Israelite tribe of Levi. He knew all about the work that the priests in Israel did. But he could not do a priest's work in God's house in Jerusalem (the temple). He was living in Babylon. King Nebuchadnezzar had taken many important people from Jerusalem. He had taken them to his city, Babylon. God had let him do this because Israel's people had worshipped other gods.\n\nGod spoke to Ezekiel, and God made him a prophet. We think that God began to give him messages in about 593 BC. Ezekiel became God's messenger to Israel's people. He spoke to all the Jews who lived in Babylon.\n\nSome Jews remained in Jerusalem. They thought that they were important. They thought that they were better than the Jews in Babylon. God said that Ezekiel must speak to the people in Babylon. He said that he would punish the people in Jerusalem. That was because they had not obeyed his rules. The prophet Jeremiah had already said this to the people in Jerusalem. But they would not listen to Jeremiah.\n\nThe Bible says that the Lord God rules all the earth. Ezekiel believed this. He believed that God was holy. And he gave great honour to God. The Israelites in Babylon listened to Ezekiel. They believed that he was God's prophet.",
    "Daniel": "The events in the Book of Daniel began in about 600 BC.\n\nGod's special people, the Israelites, did not obey God. So he punished them. He let Nebuchadnezzar, the king of Babylon, win against the Israelites who lived in Judah and its capital city, Jerusalem. We call those Israelites ‘Jews’. Nebuchadnezzar took away almost all the Jews to live in Babylon. We call that the exile.\n\nDaniel and his friends were among the Jews that Nebuchadnezzar took to Babylon. Daniel became a very important officer in the government of Babylon.\n\nThe first part of the book (Daniel 1-6) tells us about things that happened to Daniel and his friends when they lived in Babylon. Many times, the people of Babylon tried to make them turn against God. They wanted them to worship idols or to worship the king. The people in Babylon even tried to kill Daniel and his friends because they would only worship the true God. But Daniel and his friends knew that idols are not really gods. So they continued to worship the Lord God.\n\nThe second part of the book (Daniel 7-12) tells us about Daniel's visions. They were special dreams that God gave to Daniel. God showed Daniel what would happen in future years. Some things that Daniel saw in his dreams have already happened. Other things that God showed Daniel in his dreams have not yet happened. But God will do all the things that he has promised to do.",
    "Hosea": "Hosea was a prophet who lived in about 750 BC. He usually gave his messages to the people of Israel, the kingdom in the north. But some messages were for Judah's people, the kingdom in the south. If we want to understand this book, we need to understand God's covenant with the Israelites at Mount Sinai. Sinai was the place where God gave his laws to Moses.\n\nThe good things and bad things that Hosea speaks about are part of this covenant. Hosea's job was to tell his people that there was danger. God wanted his people to obey the covenant. He wanted the Israelites to live in the right way. But they did not obey God's laws, so God needed to punish them.\n\nHosea said that there would be death and disease in Israel. He also said that soldiers from another country would destroy their nation. They would take the Israelites away as their prisoners. After that, God would be able to do good things for Israel again.\n\nWe know very little about Hosea and his family. God told him to marry a prostitute who would not be a faithful to him as his wife. That was a picture of the Israelites who were not faithful to God. Hosea wanted the people to turn back to God and to obey him. If they did that, they could know God in a true way.",
    "Joel": "Joel was a prophet who may have lived in Judah. We do not know much about him or when he spoke God's message.\n\nJoel told Israel's people that God would punish them. They thought that on the day of the Lord, he would bless them and he would punish their enemies. But Joel said that God would punish his people, and after that he would again show his love to them.\n\nJoel told Israel's people that they needed to turn back to God and obey him. God would not bless them unless they did that. He wanted them to know that the day of the Lord is a day when God will judge everyone.\n\nThe apostle Peter used Joel's message to tell people about the Holy Spirit. See Acts 2:17-21 and Joel 2:28-32.",
    "Amos": "Amos came from a town called Tekoa. It was near Jerusalem, the capital city of Judah. He was a shepherd who took care of sheep.\n\nThe country on the north side of Judah was called Israel. The capital city of Israel was Samaria. Israel's king in Samaria was called Jeroboam. He was Israel's second king with that name. Judah's king in Jerusalem at that time was called Uzziah.\n\nGod's temple was in Jerusalem. The Israelites met there to worship God and to offer sacrifices. But the kings of Israel did not like it when their people went to Judah to worship God. So a long time ago, King Jeroboam I had made a place to worship God in Israel. It was in the town of Bethel. God was not happy about that. God chose Amos to leave his home in Judah and go and speak to the people of Israel. God told Amos what he should say to them.\n\nIn this book, we read God's message that Amos spoke to the people of Israel. Amos also explains the visions that God showed him.",
    "Obadiah": "There were many wars between the Israelites and the people from Edom. Genesis 27 and Numbers 20:14-21 tell us why these wars happened.\n\nGod gave Obadiah a message for the Israelites who lived in Judah. He does this after Babylon's army has destroyed Jerusalem. People from Edom were happy when Babylon's army attacked Jerusalem. They refused to help God's people. So God was angry with the people of Edom. He warned them in this message that he gave to Obadiah.\n\nIn his message, God tells the Israelites that he still loves them. He remembers what the people of Edom did. God tells the Israelites that he will punish the people of Edom. God's people will be powerful once again.",
    "Jonah": "This book tells us about what happened to a prophet called Jonah. Jonah lived in Israel, at the east end of the Mediterranean Sea. We also read about Jonah in 2 Kings 14:25.\n\nNineveh was the capital city of Assyria, a country to the north-east of Israel. The country is called Iraq today. The Assyrian people were enemies of God's people in Israel. They were cruel people.\n\nWhen God told Jonah to go to Nineveh, Jonah was not happy. He knew that God was kind. He thought that God might forgive the people there when they heard his message. Jonah did not want God to forgive Israel's enemies. So Jonah tried to run away from God. He got on a ship to go far away from Nineveh.\n\nFinally, Jonah had to obey God and go to Nineveh. The Assyrian people obeyed God's message that Jonah spoke to them. Jonah was not happy when God decided that he would not destroy Nineveh.\n\nThis book shows us that God rules over everything. He uses a storm, a big fish, a plant and a worm to teach Jonah what is right. We learn that God wants to forgive people if they turn away from their sins. He shows his love to everyone, not only to his own people, the Israelites.",
    "Micah": "Micah lived in Israel's southern kingdom, Judah. He was a prophet. He spoke God's messages to Israel's people between about 740 BC and 686 BC. The prophet Isaiah also spoke messages from God to Israel's people at that time.\n\nAfter King Solomon died, the nation of Israel became two kingdoms. The kingdom in the north was called Israel. The kingdom in the south was called Judah. Israel's capital city was Samaria. Judah's capital city was Jerusalem.\n\nIn this book, Micah speaks God's messages to the people of Samaria and the people of Jerusalem. He tells them that God is angry with them because they have refused to obey him. So God will cause enemies to attack them. But Micah also speaks about good things that God has promised. God has promised that one day he will bring his people back to worship him. God's chosen king would rule over his people and he would take care of them.",
    "Nahum": "In this book, Nahum tells the people in Nineveh that God will punish them.\n\nNineveh was the capital city of Assyria. At that time, the people in Assyria were very rich and powerful. They were also very cruel. They were enemies of God's people in Israel and Judah. They attacked God's people and the people of other countries.\n\nGod had already sent the prophet Jonah to warn the people of Nineveh. Those people believed Jonah, and they decided to obey God. So God did not punish them at that time.\n\nBut then the people did wrong things again, so God was angry with them again. Nahum told them that God would punish them for all the wrong things that they had done.\n\nAfter Nahum said these things, Babylon's army did come and destroy Nineveh. This happened in about 612 BC.",
    "Habakkuk": "Habakkuk lived in Judah about 600 years BC. Judah was the Israelite kingdom in the south. We know very little about Habakkuk himself.\n\nThe nation that ruled that part of the world until about 612 BC was Assyria. At that time, a nation called Babylon won a war against Assyria. Then the Babylonians ruled that part of the world. Both the Assyrians and the Babylonians worshipped false gods.\n\nHabakkuk wanted God to punish his people because of their sins. God said that he would use the Babylonians to punish the people of Judah. Habakkuk could not understand why God would use such wicked people to punish his own people. The Babylonians were very bad and cruel people. So Habakkuk complained to God. God explained to Habakkuk what he was doing. He would use the Babylonians to punish Judah, but finally he would punish the Babylonians.\n\nIn Chapter 3, Habakkuk prays to God. Now he understands better what God is doing. He says that he will praise God whatever happens. He knows that God is faithful.",
    "Zephaniah": "Zephaniah was a prophet. He spoke God's messages to the people of Judah when Josiah was king. Josiah was king from about 640 to 608 BC.\n\nThe book is in three parts.\n\nIn Chapter 1, Zephaniah tells the people of Judah that God will punish them.\n\nIn Chapter 2, Zephaniah warns the people of the countries that were near Judah. He tells them that God is angry with them. He tells them that God will punish them.\n\nChapter 3 is another message to the people of Judah. God says that one day he will bring his people back from the places where their enemies have taken them as prisoners.\n\nAt this time, God's prophet Jeremiah was also giving God's messages to the people of Judah. Both Zephaniah and Jeremiah said that God loved his people. But they taught that God was angry because the people had turned away from him. They must stop doing wrong things. If they continued to worship false gods, God would certainly punish them.\n\nSome people in Judah listened to the message of God's prophets. But many people did not listen. So God sent Babylon's army to fight against them. The Babylonians destroyed Jerusalem in 586 BC.\n\nGod used Babylon's army to punish Judah's people and take them away as prisoners. But God said that his people would return home to Judah at a future time.",
    "Haggai": "God punished the people of Judah because they did not serve him in a good way. God had given his laws to them, but the people did not obey them. God sent Babylon's army to attack Jerusalem. They destroyed God's temple in the city. God sent his people to live as exiles in Babylon.\n\nAfter many years, they returned to their own country, and to Jerusalem. But they still did not serve God in the way that he wanted. So God sent his prophet Haggai to speak to them.\n\nThis book is about four messages that God gave to Haggai to tell his people. It also tells us what the people did after they heard Haggai's message.",
    "Zechariah": "The enemies of Judah's people took them as prisoners to a country called Babylon. After about 70 years, the king of Babylon let the Jews return to Jerusalem to build God's temple again. Zechariah was one of the Jews who returned. He spoke to the people of Jerusalem from about 520 BC. At that time, God's prophet Haggai was also speaking God's messages to the Jews in Jerusalem.\n\nGod told Zechariah the messages that he must speak to the Jews. An important part of his message was, ‘If you turn back to me, I will come back to you.’ See Zechariah 1:3. God gave Zechariah eight dreams. These dreams showed the Jews what would happen in future years. God would bless them and he would fight against their enemies. The last chapters promise that God will one day rule as king over the whole world. See Zechariah 14:9.",
    "Malachi": "Malachi is the name of the man who wrote this book. He spoke God's message to the Israelites who lived in Judah. Many years ago, a powerful enemy had come. Babylon's army had taken the people away from their own country, Judah. After a long time, they returned home. They built the temple again in Jerusalem. This happened in about 516 BC. Malachi wrote this book in about 460 BC.\n\nGod had promised the people that they would have many good things. But there was only a little rain, so their crops did not grow well. They did not have enough food to eat. The people thought that God did not love them. As a result, they did not obey the laws that God had given to them. Malachi knew what the people were thinking. He spoke God's message to them. He told them how they could come back to God. He told them how they could love God again.\n\nIn Chapter 3, Malachi tells them that the Lord God will return to his temple. He will come to judge his people, but also to bless them.",

    // NEW TESTAMENT
    "Matthew": "A man called Matthew wrote this book at some time between the years AD 59 and AD 70. He was also called Levi. Matthew was a Jew. His job was to take taxes from people. Then he became a disciple of Jesus. Jesus chose him to be one of the 12 apostles. Matthew wrote the book in the Greek language. He wrote it for Jews who understood Greek. In his book, Matthew wrote many things about the messages that God's prophets had written a long time ago. He showed that those messages had now become true. The Jews who read Matthew's book would know all about these things.\n\nMatthew tells us the good news about the kingdom of God. He tells us about Jesus' birth and his life. He tells us how Jesus died. He tells us how Jesus rose to life again after his death. He went to live in heaven with God again. Matthew also tells us why Jesus came to live in the world. He explains the things that Jesus taught people. He tells us about many things that Jesus did.\n\nThe Jews were waiting for God to send a special person to them. They called this person the Messiah. The Greek word for Messiah is Christ. That is why Jesus is called Christ.",
    "Mark": "Mark probably wrote this book while he was living in Rome. He wrote it at some time between AD 50 and AD 70. Mark was also called John Mark. It is the shortest one of the four Gospels. Mark wrote his book for Gentiles. \n\nMark wanted to tell everyone about the things that Jesus had done. He described how Jesus lived. He explained who Jesus was. Jesus was a man, but he was also God's Son. Mark described how Jesus died on a cross. And he described how Jesus became alive again after his death. He explained how people could let God rule in their lives (the kingdom of God). He wrote about the things that Jesus taught the people.\n\nPeople think that Mark was a friend of Peter, who was one of Jesus' apostles. \n\nMark listened to Peter when he was talking about Jesus. He wrote down the things that Peter said. People also think that Mark was the young man in Mark 14:51-52. If that man was Mark, then he saw some of those things himself.",
    "Luke": "Luke was a doctor who was a disciple of Jesus. He was probably not a Jew. He wrote this book some time between the years AD 59 and AD 80. He wrote it for a friend called Theophilus who was an important person. Luke wanted people to know what was true about Jesus.\n\nLuke tells us the good news about the kingdom of God. That means that God wants to rule in the lives of his people. Those people may be Jews or they may be Gentiles. Luke tells us about Jesus' birth. He also tells us about his life and his death. Luke explains to us why Jesus came to the world and what he did during his life here. Then he tells us how he went back to heaven to live with his Father God again. At the end, Luke explains to us about God's gift of his Holy Spirit. Luke wanted everyone to know what Jesus said and what he did.\n\nLuke also wrote the Book of Acts.",
    "John": "John's Gospel is one of the four Gospels. Those are the books that tell us about Jesus' life on earth. ‘Gospel’ means ‘good news’. John was one of the three apostles who knew Jesus best. John called himself ‘the disciple that Jesus loved’. We think that John wrote his Gospel some years after Matthew, Mark and Luke wrote their Gospels.\n\nJohn's Gospel tells us about who Jesus was, as the Son of God. Jesus is the only person who can give us true life with God. John teaches us more about God's Holy Spirit too.\n\nAt the beginning of his Gospel, John calls Jesus ‘the Word’. Jesus is the one that God sent into the world so that we could see and understand his message of grace and truth.",
    "Acts": "The name of this book, ‘Acts’, is short for ‘The Acts of the Apostles’. It tells us what the apostles and other Christians did after Jesus went back to heaven.\n\nLuke probably wrote this book in about the year AD 63. Luke was probably not a Jew but he became a disciple of Jesus. He was a doctor, and he was one of Paul's friends. Sometimes he went with Paul when Paul travelled from country to country. He went to Rome with Paul and he stayed there with him. So he saw many of the things that he tells us about in the book.\n\nLuke wrote this book to send to Theophilus. This is the second book that Luke wrote for him. The first book is called ‘The Gospel of Luke’. In Acts, Luke tells us how God first gave his Holy Spirit to people who believed in Jesus. He tells how the apostles continued to serve Jesus in Jerusalem and in many other places. He tells us how more and more people believed in Jesus. He also describes how some Christians argued with each other about Christian teaching. Some of these were Jewish believers and some were Gentile believers.\n\nLuke also tells us that the leaders of the Jews did not believe in Jesus. They wanted the apostles to stop teaching people about Jesus. So they caused a lot of trouble for the believers.",
    "Romans": "Paul was probably staying in the city of Corinth when he wrote this letter. Corinth was in the southern part of the country that we call Greece. Paul wrote this letter in about the year AD 57.\n\nPaul wrote this letter to the Christians who were living in the city of Rome. When he wrote this letter, Paul himself had never visited Rome. But he hoped to go there soon.\n\nSome of the Christians in Rome were Jews and some of them were Gentiles. There may have been problems between the Jewish Christians and the Gentile Christians, because they thought about things differently. They may have been meeting in separate groups, in different places. So Paul knew that he had to explain his message to both Jewish Christians and Gentile Christians.\n\nSome Jewish Christians thought that Gentile Christians should obey the Jewish rules that God had given to Moses.\n\nSo, in this letter, Paul writes about the purpose of the Jewish rules. Those rules were very good and very important. They helped Israel's people to obey God. But Paul explains why those rules could not save people from their sins.",
    "I Corinthians": "Paul wrote this letter to the Christians at Corinth. Corinth was an important city in the country that we now call Greece. It was in Achaia, which was in the south of Greece. Paul had stayed at Corinth for 18 months. Many people became Christians while he was there. Most of the Christians there were Gentiles. While Paul was with them, he explained God's message to them. See Acts 18:11.\n\nPaul wrote this letter in about the year AD 54.\n\nAfter he had left Corinth, Paul heard news about some problems among the Christians there. Also, the Christians at Corinth had written a letter to Paul to ask him questions about certain things. See 1 Corinthians 7:1.\n\nIn his letter, Paul answers some questions that the Corinthian Christians had asked. He explains why the Christians were thinking in the wrong way about some things. He tells them how they should live to please God.",
    "II Corinthians": "Paul wrote this letter to the Christians in Corinth. Corinth was a city in Achaia, which was in the south of Greece. Paul wrote this letter in about AD 55. Somebody among the Christians at Corinth had been doing very wrong things. Also, some of the Christians had been listening to false teachers. Some of the false teachers were saying that Paul was not Christ's servant.\n\nPaul had written to the people at Corinth before. He had visited there twice. Before he wrote this letter, Paul had met his friend Titus again. Titus had just returned from a visit to Corinth. He told Paul good news about the Christians there. So Paul wrote this letter to say that he was happy to hear this good news. He says that he will visit Corinth again soon. He does not want to be angry with the Christians there. But he will be angry with anyone who is still doing wrong things.",
    "Galatians": "Paul wrote this letter to the Christians who lived in Galatia. Galatia was a part of the country that we now call Turkey. Paul had visited many towns in Galatia. As a result of his visits, many people there had become Christians. Most of these Christians were not Jewish. They were Gentiles. But after Paul had left Galatia, certain Jewish believers visited them. They told the Gentile Christians, ‘You cannot really be God's people unless you let someone circumcise you, as we Jews do.’\n\nPaul was angry because those Jewish believers had been teaching wrong ideas to the Christians. He was sad that the Christians in Galatia had accepted those wrong ideas. In his letter he told them more clearly why they did not need to obey the Jewish rules, like circumcision. When Jesus Christ died on the cross, his sacrifice was enough to save us from our sins.",
    "Ephesians": "Paul probably wrote this letter when he was in Rome, in about the year AD 62. Paul was in a prison in Rome. He wrote this letter to the church that was at Ephesus. Ephesus was a city in the south and west part of the country that now is called Turkey. Paul may also have sent this letter to other groups of Christians for them to read.\n\nPaul explains the great things that Jesus Christ has done on behalf of all people. Christ has taken away everything that caused people to be against God and against each other. Now all people, both Jews and Gentiles, can become God's people. They need to believe in Jesus Christ and become united with him. All Christians belong to one family, and Christ is the leader of that family.\n\nPaul explains how Christians should live to please God. As one family, we must try to agree with each other. We must continue to love each other. We must learn how to be strong as Christians. We must be ready to fight against the devil when he attacks us.",
    "Philippians": "Paul wrote this letter while he was in a prison in Rome. At that time, Rome's ruler (Caesar) was very powerful and he ruled over many countries. Paul wrote this letter in about the year AD 62. At that time, Philippi was an important city in Macedonia.\n\nPaul first visited Philippi about 12 years before he wrote this letter. He went there to teach the people about Jesus. Some people there became angry about the things that Paul was doing. So they put Paul in prison. See Acts 16:11-40. We think that Paul visited Philippi again after that. He may have gone there several times.\n\nIn his letter, Paul tells the Christians that Jesus Christ is much more important to him than anything else. The purpose of Paul's life is to tell people about Christ.\n\nPaul wants the Christians at Philippi to obey God completely as Christ did. Paul is afraid that they might listen to false teachers who were teaching wrong ideas. Paul wants the Christians to do things that make God happy. They must continue to trust God. They must continue to obey God, even when other people cause them to suffer.\n\nPaul thanks the Christians at Philippi for the gifts that they had sent to him. He tells them that he will send Timothy and Epaphroditus to Philippi. These men will tell the Christians there the news about Paul.",
    "Colossians": "Colossae was a city in the Roman region called Asia. Asia was the south and west part of the country that we now call Turkey. When Paul wrote this letter, the Roman people were very powerful. They ruled many countries. Rome is the capital of the country that we now call Italy.\n\nWe think that Paul himself never visited Colossae. Instead, a man called Epaphras went there to tell the good news about Jesus Christ to the people.\n\nAfter that, when Paul was in a prison, Epaphras visited him. Epaphras told Paul the news about the Christians who lived at Colossae. Then Paul wrote this letter to them while he was still in the prison.\n\nEpaphras had told Paul that false teachers were teaching wrong things to the Christians at Colossae. The false teachers were saying that Christians must obey the same rules that God told the Jews to obey. Also, they were teaching other wrong ideas.\n\nSo Paul tells the Christians that they should not believe those false teachers. Only Jesus Christ can save us from all the wrong things that we do. Jesus made the world. And he wants to save the people who live in it. We need to believe in him. Then, in our spirits, we die with Christ and we become alive again with him. We become new people, with a new nature.",
    "I Thessalonians": "Thessalonica was a large city in Macedonia. Macedonia included the north part of the country that we call Greece. It also included part of the country that we call North Macedonia. Thessalonica was an important port. Roads from several different directions joined there.\n\nPaul went to Thessalonica to teach the people about Jesus Christ. He stayed there for only a short time, perhaps only a few weeks. Two other men, called Silas and Timothy, went there with him. As a result of what Paul taught them, some Jews in Thessalonica believed in Christ. Many other people who were not Jews ( Gentiles) also believed. But the Jews who refused to believe Christ caused a lot of trouble for Paul and his friends. Paul had to leave the city at night.\n\nPaul, together with Silas and Timothy, wrote this letter in about the year AD 50 or AD 51. So this letter may be the first of Paul's letters that we have in the Bible. Paul wrote it only a few months after he had first taught the Christian message at Thessalonica. So he was writing to people who had been Christians for only a short time.\n\nPaul teaches them about how they should do good, right things, to make God happy. And he teaches them about Jesus' return to the earth.",
    "II Thessalonians": "Thessalonica was a large city in Macedonia. Macedonia included the north part of the country that we call Greece. It also included part of the country that we call North Macedonia. We think that Paul, together with Silas and Timothy, went to Thessalonica about the year AD 50. Paul went there for a short time, to tell the people about Jesus. A few months after that, Paul wrote his first letter to the Christians who lived at Thessalonica.\n\nPeople told Paul some news about the Christians who lived at Thessalonica. So he wrote this second letter to them a short time later.\n\nPaul knew that some people were still causing bad trouble for the Christians at Thessalonica. So he wrote to help them to be brave. He says that God knows about their troubles. God has a purpose in everything, and he will finally punish the enemies of his people.\n\nAlso, some people were teaching that Jesus had already returned to the earth. Other people were teaching that he would return very soon. Some of the Christians may have stopped working as a result. So Paul writes to explain that certain things must happen before Jesus returns. He also says that nobody should stop working. People should work so that they can buy their own food.",
    "I Timothy": "Paul was a Christian teacher. God sent him to many countries to tell people about Jesus Christ. Timothy was a young man who had travelled with Paul on many of Paul's journeys.\n\nAfter Paul had taught in different places for many years, he was a prisoner in Rome. Paul stayed in Rome for two years. We think that he stayed there at some time between AD 59 and AD 63. After two years, we think that the Romans allowed Paul to leave Rome. So then Paul started travelling and teaching the Christian message again. Timothy went with him to Ephesus, a big city in the country that we call Turkey.\n\nPaul chose Timothy to be the leader of the Christians in Ephesus. When Paul wrote this first letter to Timothy, Paul had left Ephesus. But he had told Timothy to stay there. Some people in Ephesus were teaching the Christians wrong things. These false teachers had caused some of the Christians to obey the wrong ideas that they taught. So Paul wrote to tell Timothy to stop their false teaching.\n\nIn this letter, Paul is teaching Timothy how to lead the Christians in Ephesus. Paul also describes how all Christian leaders should live. He says that they should be good examples for other people to copy.",
    "II Timothy": "This is Paul's second letter to Timothy. He wrote it from a prison in Rome. They had put Paul in prison because they did not like Christians. Timothy was a young man who had travelled with Paul on many journeys.\n\nSome time earlier, Paul had made Timothy the leader of the Christians in Ephesus. Ephesus was a city in the country that we call Turkey. We think that Timothy was still in Ephesus when Paul wrote this letter to him.\n\nWe think that Paul wrote this letter at some time between AD 64 and AD 67.\n\nAmong the Christians at Ephesus, there were some people who were teaching wrong things. In his first letter to Timothy, Paul had told Timothy to stop those teachers. He told Timothy to teach the true Christian message. And in this letter, he tells Timothy to continue teaching it.\n\nWhen Paul writes this letter, he knows that he will die soon. He wants to see Timothy again before he dies. Also, he wants Timothy to be ready for trouble. Timothy must remember that it is very important to obey Christ. He must continue to live in a way that pleases Christ.\n\nWe think that this is the last letter in the Bible that Paul wrote. We think that the Romans killed him a short time after he wrote it.",
    "Titus": "Paul was a great Christian teacher. God sent him to many countries to tell people about Jesus Christ. Titus was a young man who had travelled with Paul. He had been to Jerusalem with Paul. See Galatians 2:1-3. Some time after that, Paul sent Titus to the city of Corinth. There were serious problems among the Christians at Corinth. Paul sent Titus there to help them. See 2 Corinthians 7:5-16; 8:16-24.\n\nWe think that Paul wrote this letter between AD 62 and AD 66. Titus had travelled with Paul again. But Paul had asked him to stay on the island called Crete. Crete is in the Mediterranean Sea, near the countries called Greece and Turkey. Paul left Crete and he travelled to other places. But Titus stayed on Crete, to help the Christians there.\n\nThe Christians who lived on Crete had been believers for only a short time. They needed good leaders. So in this letter, Paul tells Titus what kind of people he should choose as leaders. There were some false teachers there. So Paul tells Titus that he must not let the Christians believe those false teachers. Titus must teach only the true Christian message. He must tell the Christians to do good things that please God.",
    "Philemon": "Paul was in prison when he wrote this letter to Philemon. He was in prison because he taught people about Jesus. We think that Paul wrote this letter in about AD 60.\n\nPhilemon was a Christian who lived in the town of Colossae. Colossae was in the south and west part of Turkey. Philemon had become a Christian because Paul had taught him about Jesus Christ. A man called Onesimus was one of Philemon's slaves. The name Onesimus means ‘good helper’.\n\nWe think that Onesimus had robbed Philemon and then he ran away.\n\nOnesimus visited Paul, and Paul taught him about Jesus. As a result, Onesimus believed in Jesus and he became a Christian. After that, Paul wrote this letter and he gave it to Onesimus. Then he sent Onesimus back to Philemon at Colossae. Paul wanted Onesimus to give the letter to Philemon.\n\nIn his letter, Paul asks Philemon to forgive Onesimus. It was difficult for Onesimus to return to Philemon. Philemon could have killed Onesimus because of what he had done.\n\nWhen Paul wrote to Philemon, he also wrote a letter to the Christians at Colossae. That letter is in the Bible. It is called Colossians. Tychicus was a friend of Paul and he was also a Christian. Tychicus took both letters from Paul to Colossae. He travelled with Onesimus.",
    "Hebrews": "The Book of Hebrews is a letter to a group of Christians. ‘Hebrews’ is another name for Jewish people. So probably the letter was written to believers who were Jews.\n\nWe do not know who wrote the Book of Hebrews. Most people agree that the writer wrote this letter in about AD 60-70.\n\nThe letter says a lot about God's promises to the Israelites. It talks about the tabernacle and how the Israelites worshipped God there. They killed animals so that God would forgive them for the wrong things that they had done. God's old covenant with his people showed them how they should live. God's Law had many rules for them to obey.\n\nThe writer of this letter shows that Jesus Christ has given us a new way to come to God. The writer wants to help the Jewish believers to trust Jesus and his death on the cross.\n\nWe know that other people were causing a lot of trouble for these Christians. So the writer is trying to help them to live well as Christians. They should never stop trusting Christ.",
    "James": "James wrote his letter to tell Christians what they should do. He also told them what they should not do. James did not write it to tell people how to become Christians. He is writing to Christians. They know that Jesus died for them. He is writing to help them to live in a way that pleases Jesus Christ.\n\nAfter he had written his letter, he sent it to churches in many places. It is important for all Christians today. James was the brother of the Lord Jesus. James was also a leader of the church in Jerusalem.",
    "I Peter": "Peter was one of the 12 men that Jesus chose to be his apostles. Peter's name was Simon, but Jesus changed it to Peter. ‘Peter’ means a ‘rock’ or a ‘stone’.\n\nPeter wrote this letter to groups of Christians in several different places. All of those places were in the country that we now call Turkey. We think that he wrote it about the year AD 65. Peter may have been in Rome when he wrote it.\n\nAt that time, enemies were causing a lot of trouble and pain for Christians. These enemies were killing many Christians. As a result, many Christians were afraid. Peter wrote to them because he wanted to help them. He wanted them to be brave. He wanted them to continue to trust Jesus strongly.\n\nIn his letter, Peter describes the great things that God has done on our behalf. He says that, as Christians, we will have trouble and pain during our lives on this earth. But we must remember that God knows about all our troubles. And he lets us have troubles sometimes because he wants to make us like Jesus. Jesus had much trouble and pain on our behalf, but he never stopped obeying God. Peter says that all Christians should obey people with authority. And Christians should always do what is right and good.",
    "II Peter": "Peter was one of the 12 men that Jesus chose to be his apostles. Peter's name was Simon, but Jesus changed it to Peter. ‘Peter’ means a ‘rock’ or a ‘stone’.\n\nThis is the second letter that Peter wrote. Almost certainly, he wrote this letter at some time between the years AD 65 and 68. Peter probably died soon after he wrote this letter.\n\nPeter wrote this letter to Christians who wanted to obey God. Some false teachers were teaching wrong ideas about Jesus and God. So Peter wrote this letter to help the Christians. He wanted them to believe in God and Jesus more strongly. He told them not to believe the false teachers. God would destroy the false teachers because they were so bad.\n\nAlso, Peter told the Christians to be like people who are watching carefully. They should be ready for Jesus, because he would certainly come back to the earth.",
    "I John": "John who wrote this letter was the apostle John. He also wrote two other letters (2 John and 3 John), as well as John's Gospel and the Book of Revelation.\n\nThese three letters have ideas very like those that John wrote about in his Gospel. The Gospel and these letters all speak about God's love and the light that God gives. When John speaks about light, he means that God shows us the truth. This means that we can live in a way that pleases him. If people are living in the dark, they do not know the truth about God.\n\nJohn also talks about the world in a special way. People who belong to the world are people who do not know God.\n\nJohn's Gospel tells people about Jesus and his life. It tells people how Jesus is the way to know God. John shows that Jesus is the Son of God. He wanted people to know that Jesus had died to save them. He wrote these letters to help people who already believe in Jesus. He tells believers how God wants them to live. He also wrote this letter to speak against the message of false teachers that some Christians had heard.",
    "II John": "John who wrote this letter was the apostle John. He also wrote the letters 1 John and 3 John, as well as John's Gospel and the Book of Revelation.\n\nJohn calls himself a leader of the church. He had authority over several churches. He was an old man and he called the Christians ‘my little children’. He wrote his letters for people to read aloud in church meetings. He called the churches that he was writing to, ‘a special lady and her children’. He is warning these churches that they should not accept false teachers. Teachers that are like this do not teach the true message of Jesus.",
    "III John": "John who wrote this letter was the apostle John. He also wrote the letters 1 John and 2 John, as well as John's Gospel and the Book of Revelation. John was an old man. He talks about believers as if they are his children.\n\nJohn wrote this letter to a person called Gaius. John is sad, because Diotrephes is causing Christians to have problems. Also, Diotrephes is saying bad things about John. He is telling lies. John is warning Gaius not to copy Diotrephes.",
    "Jude": "Jude's letter is a message to Christians about false teachers, who were teaching wrong things. Those teachers said that they themselves were Christians. But they were very dangerous, because they stopped some people from obeying God. God is very angry with false teachers like that, and he will punish them.\n\nJude tells the Christians that they must be very careful. They must continue to believe the right things that God's true message teaches. They must continue to love God and other people. They must try to help their friends who have believed the wrong things.\n\nWe do not know which Christians Jude was writing to. Nor do we know when he wrote his letter. But Jude's message is very important for all Christians at any time.",
    "Revelation": "Revelation is the last book in the Bible. It includes many ideas that we find in other books in the Bible. It tells us about future events from John's time, until now, and until the end of this world.\n\nJesus' apostle, John, wrote the book for Christians. At that time, things were very difficult for Christians. The Roman ruler (Caesar) was causing a lot of trouble for them. John was a prisoner because he was a Christian.\n\nJesus appeared to John in a special dream. He also sent an angel to John. The angel showed John many future events that surprised him. Jesus told John to write down what he saw. Jesus wants us to know about things that will happen during the last days of the earth. He wants us to be ready.\n\n‘Revelation’ means ‘to show things that people could not see before’. Many of the events in this book are like pictures. They show us an idea of what will really happen. Jesus wants us to think about these pictures. He wants us to understand as much as we can.\n\nOne day, Jesus will return to this earth. He will finally win against all his enemies. He will put right everything that is wrong. And all those who love him will live with him always. Nothing will ever hurt them or make them sad again. Revelation tells us to remember this. It teaches us to wait patiently."
};